How do you recrystallize a product from methanol?

Practically speaking, I usually add what seems like a reasonable amount of solvent to dissolve it and I heat it to a boil. If it’s boiling, and everything isn’t dissolved I add a little more methanol. Repeat this until it all goes in. Remove it from the heat and let it cool slowly. You should see some nice looking crystals form.

What are the reasons to use two solvents in recrystallization?

Two solvents are used in recrystallization in order to either induce crystallization or to improve the growth of crystals. For example say a compound has poor solubility in petroleum spirit (60–80) regardless of the temperature. A second solvent, typically with a lower b.p., but the compound of interest is very soluble in it (e.g. diethyl ether), can be used in the recrystallisation.

How do you recrystallize a product from methanol?

The steps in the recrystallization of a compound are:

  1. Find a suitable solvent for the recrystallization;
  2. Dissolve the impure solid in a minimum volume of hot solvent;
  3. Remove any insoluble impurities by filtration;
  4. Slowly cool the hot solution to crystallize the desired compound from the solution;
  5. Filter the solution to isolate the purified solid compound.

What are examples of good recrystallization solvents?

The best solvent is one in which your compound is very soluble when hot but only partially soluble when cooled to room temp.. This is going to be different for each compound, but if you have a choice, it’s good to use a liquid that’s at least more volatile and easier to remove than something like water.

Another trick you can use is to control your rate of cooling so that your compound doesn’t fall out as an amorphous solid. Sometimes I find that allowing a flask to cool resting in a beaker of hot water slows gives nicer crystals.

What is a good solvent for recrystalization?

For organic solutes, usually the best solvent is ethyl alcohol. Why? Well, clearly, ethyl alcohol has polar and non-polar functionality, the hydroxyl tail, and the hydrocarbyl chain. Organic solutes TEND to have some solubility in the HOT alcohol, and on cooling the solute crystallizes out… As a bonus, ethyl alcohol is cheap, smells nice, and is not too hard on your hands (tho it does sting on cuts!). The ethyl alcohol we use in the lab is often so-called industrial methylated spiritindustrial methylated spirit, i.e. ethyl alcohol denatured with a BIT of methyl alcohol added, so that you can’t drink it ….

Why is the choice of solvent important in recrystallization?

A crystallization procedure may not work, or not work well, depending on the solvent. If you have a compound as a solution in a certain solvent, you could crystallize it by lowering the temperature, or by adding a second solvent. The compound of interest may come out of solution by crystallizing or by precipitating as an amorphous solid rather than a crystalline one. The procedure can be repeatable regardless of scale, or it may be somewhat to very difficult to obtain reproducible results.

What is the single solvents recrystallization process?

This takes advantage of the higher solubility of solids at higher temperatures. A suspension of the substance is heated to dissolve the material of interest and then filtered to remove insoluble impurities. The filtrate is allowed to cool slowly and is often “seeded” with crystals of the desired product during cooling. The product is collected by filtration, washed with a bit of solvent, again pulled dry, then usually dried in a vacuum oven.

For highly soluble material, it is sometimes advantageous to dissolve the material at room temperature and cool in a fridge or freezer.

What is the multi-solvent recrystallization process?

Don’t know why you’re asking this on Quora? Recrystallization of solids in order to increase purity is commonly done by a combination of heat and solvent manipulation. Heat consists of heating (to increase solubility) and cooling (to decrease solubility); solvent manipulation consists of dissolving the solid in a good solvent, then adding a non-solvent (but one miscible with the first solvent) bit by bit. Why do you seldom see high boiling point solvents used as a recrystallization solvent?

Because recrystallization is dependent on evaporation of the solvent.

If you use a high boiling point solvent then it will take much more energy and effort to achieve that evaporation, and the temperatures involved may negatively impact the substance you want to recrystallize.

Why make it harder than you need to. Use a “low” boiling point solvent that will still achieve your aims.

What are the criteria in choosing a good recrystallization solvent?
  1. There must be no chemical reaction between the solute and the solvent
  2. Solute should be moderately soluble in the selected solvent. It means not very high or very low.
  3. Solvent should possess a low boiling point. This is required to prepare a super saturated solution for crystallization.

How do I separate crystals from a solution after recrystallization?

Add the solution containing the crystals to a buchner funnel containing filter paper if you are planning to use vacuum filtration or a funnel containing filter paper if your gravity filtering it. Add the solution to the filter and allow the crystals to collect in the funnel as the solution flows into a beaker for collection. Wash and agitate the crystals to ensure that impuries are removed (use the cold solvent that was used in the recrystallisation). Pull a vacuum until the product is fairly dry (if you’re vacuum filtering) and then transfer to a watch glass to completely dry.
